  data-notes: "As you'll remember both Ian and I have said on a number of occasions, once we get to the end of 1914 or so, much of the rest of the course covers various attempts to break the stalemate of the Western Front. As Ian mentioned, this might consist of new technologies, like airplanes or tanks or poison gas, which we'll get to; it might consist of attempts simply to use main force, as in creeping barrages or going over the top in great numbers; or it might involve using flanking maneuvers. Today we'll look at one of those flanking maneuvers. It's a very small, maybe even simple story, but with big ramifications. It drags on for essentially the entirety of 1915, and it has consequences that touch the British high command, as well as the future of Turkey.

We also want, as I've said previously, to look at nationalism. And the story of Gallipoli is a story about nationalism on both sides; it remains to this day a foundational story of Australian and New Zealander nationalism, based on their treatment at the hands of the British Empire. It's also vital to certain personalities---Winston Churchill in particular, but also Mustafa Kemal.

So there's a lot to get out of this single battle."
